 Yes. I think the clean understanding is:

  AMDGPU waiting on the io_uring/io_dmabuf fence is not inherently wrong. The fence means:

  NVMe may still be using the old DMA mapping.
  Do not move/reuse the BO memory until that DMA is done.

  So AMDGPU should wait for it before moving the BO.

  The problem is not “AMDGPU waits on the fence.”

  The problem is where and while holding what locks AMDGPU waits on that fence.

  The Deadlock Shape

  In v4, invalidation does this:

  AMDGPU holds dmabuf->resv
    -> calls invalidate_mappings()
      -> io_dmabuf adds token fence to dmabuf->resv
      -> io_dmabuf kills map refs
      -> returns immediately

  Later, after I/O refs drain:

  io_dmabuf_map_release_work
    -> signals token fence
    -> tries to lock dmabuf->resv
    -> unmaps old attachment

  Meanwhile restore does:

  KFD restore locks BO reservation locks
  KFD restore waits on token fence while still holding those locks

  So the bad dependency is:

  KFD restore:
    holds dmabuf->resv
    waits for io_dmabuf fence

  io_dmabuf cleanup:
    must run to finish old-map cleanup
    after signaling, tries to acquire dmabuf->resv
    blocked by KFD restore

  Even if the fence is signaled before the release worker takes the lock, the design is still fragile because KFD may
  wait on another token fence that has not reached its release worker yet. With many jobs/BOs, this is a process-wide
  lock hold problem.

  The Real Bug

  The real bug is the async invalidation model:

  add fence now
  return to exporter
  finish unmap later in a worker that needs the same resv lock

  That creates a window where the exporter/KFD can wait on importer progress while still holding locks that the importer
  cleanup/remap path needs.

  So AMDGPU is doing a reasonable thing by waiting for “DMA stopped.” io_dmabuf is also doing a reasonable thing by
  signaling after I/O refs drain. The broken part is splitting invalidation into:

  fence added under resv
  cleanup/unmap deferred outside that lock
  cleanup later needs to reacquire resv

  The Fix

  Best fix conceptually:

  Do not use an async token fence + later release worker.
  Make invalidation synchronous.

  That means when AMDGPU calls invalidate_mappings() while holding dmabuf->resv:

  io_dmabuf:
    remove active map
    stop new users
    wait for in-flight I/O refs to drain
    unmap immediately while resv is still held
    return

  Then:

  No token fence is added to dmabuf->resv.
  No release worker needs to reacquire dmabuf->resv.
  AMDGPU waits directly inside invalidate until old DMA is gone.

  The cost is AMDGPU eviction waits for outstanding NVMe I/O. But that wait is bounded by I/O completion and avoids the
  lock/fence cycle.

  So the shortest answer:

  AMDGPU waiting is right.
  The deadlock is caused by io_dmabuf returning from invalidate before unmap is done,
  then trying to finish unmap later from a worker that needs the same reservation lock
  AMDGPU/KFD may still be holding while waiting.

  The fix is synchronous invalidation/drain/unmap, or otherwise redesign so the deferred worker never needs to reacquire
  the exporter’s reservation lock.

